    correctAnswer: 'D',
    preTeaching: 'CAUSALITY VS. ARGUMENT STRUCTURE\n\nBefore we dive into this question, let\'s return to the topic of causality vs argument structure. It\'s a subject which confuses even the most advanced students.\n\nRemember: if there is a cause and effect relationship in a LR argument, don\'t automatically assume that the cause is the premise and the effect is the conclusion.\n\nEXAMPLE 1 \u2014 John & Netflix:\nJohn couldn\'t wake up on time for his morning class. John usually has trouble waking up in the morning when he stays up late watching Netflix. Therefore John probably has been binge watching Netflix again last night.\n\nCause/Effect: Watching Netflix (Cause) \u2192 Cannot wake up early (Effect)\nBut structurally:\n\u2022 Premise 1: John couldn\'t wake up early\n\u2022 Premise 2: John has trouble waking up early when he watches Netflix\n\u2022 Conclusion: John was probably watching Netflix last night\n\nThe cause is the CONCLUSION, not the premise!\n\nEXAMPLE 2 \u2014 Megan\'s Coffee (Causal Chain):\nBecause Megan missed her morning coffee she was not paying attention to her surroundings. As a result she fell down the stairs. So not getting your daily dose of caffeine can cause dangerous accidents.\n\nCausal chain: No Coffee (A) \u2192 Not Paying Attention (B) \u2192 Accident (C)\n\nBut structurally, how should we diagram this?\nThe conclusion is A \u2192 C. We have two pieces of information supporting it: A \u2192 B and B \u2192 C.\n\nIs there an intermediate conclusion? Remember that an intermediate conclusion is ALWAYS supported by a premise. Does A \u2192 B support in any way B \u2192 C? No. They are two independent causal relationships. Yes they form the same causal chain, but there is no supporting relationship between the two.\n\nStructurally:\n\u2022 Premise: A \u2192 B\n\u2022 Premise: B \u2192 C\n\u2022 Conclusion: A \u2192 C\n\nJust because there is a causal logic chain A \u2192 B \u2192 C doesn\'t mean that A is the premise, B the intermediate conclusion, and C the conclusion!\n\nEXAMPLE 3 \u2014 YLS Conditional:\nIf you went to Yale Law School, then you must have gotten a great LSAT score. Every high LSAT scorer is a proficient computer user. So all YLS students are proficient computer users.\n\nConditionally: YLS \u2192 Great LSAT \u2192 Computer Skills\nStructurally:\n\u2022 Premise: YLS \u2192 Great LSAT\n\u2022 Premise: Great LSAT \u2192 Computer Skills\n\u2022 Conclusion: YLS \u2192 Computer Skills\n\nIs "Great LSAT \u2192 Computer Skills" an intermediate conclusion? No. Because "YLS \u2192 Great LSAT" is not supporting "Great LSAT \u2192 Computer Skills." They are each independent premises that, when combined, lead to the conclusion.\n\nKEY TAKEAWAY:\nJust because a statement/idea/condition forms the middle part of a causal or conditional chain, that doesn\'t make it the intermediate conclusion. Always treat the structure of an argument (premise, intermediate conclusion, main conclusion) and the logical aspects of the argument (cause/effect, sufficient/necessary) as two distinct and separate issues!\n\nCause \u2192 Effect is NOT the same as Premise \u2192 Conclusion.\nSufficient \u2192 Necessary is NOT the same as Premise \u2192 Conclusion.',
